      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Keep the Mideast Talks Alive</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>M Donald Coleman letter says US and Israel must make clear that there is no chance that any combination of Palestinians and Arabs could run Israel to the ground</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Reuel Marc Gerecht's rigid historical determinism regarding the Middle East is wrong on two important counts (Op-Ed, Oct. 14). Far from being naive, the United States' tenacious belief in the power of the secular political process to overcome ancient animosities is the only cause for hope that the Middle East may have a future different from its past.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Reuel Marc Gerecht's rigid historical determinism regarding the Middle East is wrong on two important counts (Op-Ed, Oct. 14). Far from being naive, the United States' tenacious belief in the power of the secular political process to overcome ancient animosities is the only cause for hope that the Middle East may have a future different from its past.</p>
        <p>Even more disturbing is Mr. Gerecht's suggestion that for Arabs to make peace with Israel would be for them to forsake their history and faith. This idea seeks to rob Arabs and Muslims of their will and rationality and ignores those multitudes who are proud of their history but recognize the need for change and have their faith but are not fanatical.</p>
        <p>MAZDAK ATIGHI  Palo Alto, Calif., Oct. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
